The '''Bolivian montane dry forests''' (NT0206) is an ecoregion in Bolivia on the eastern side of the [[Andes]]. It is a transitional habitat between the puna grasslands higher up to the west and the Chaco scrub to the east. The habitat is under severe stress from a growing human population.

==Geography==

===Location===
{{location map|Bolivia|relief=yes|lat_deg=-18.367 |lon_deg=-65.039 |caption=Location in Bolivia|width=220px}}
The ecoregion is in the dry mountain valleys of the Andes in southern Bolivia. It has an area of {{convert|8,028,963|ha}}.{{sfn|Bolivian montane dry forests – Myers|loc=WWF Abstract}} In the south large areas of the ecoregion are found within the [[Central Andean puna]] and [[Southern Andean Yungas]]. To the east the dry forests transition into the [[Dry Chaco]] ecoregion. Further north smaller areas of the ecoregion are found in contact with the [[Central Andean dry puna]], [[Central Andean wet puna]] and [[Bolivian Yungas]].{{sfn|WildFinder – WWF}}

===Terrain===

The terrain is rugged, with cliffs, steep hillsides, valleys and gullies.{{sfn|Bolivian montane dry forests – Myers|loc=WWF Abstract}}

Altitudes are from {{convert|360-700|m}} above sea level.

In the east fingers of the dry forest stretch into the [[yungas]], while in the west fingers of [[puna grassland]] extend into the dry forest.{{sfn|Brooks}}

===Climate===

At a sample location at {{coord|-18.75 | -65.25}} the [[Köppen climate classification]] is "Cwb": warm temperate, winter dry, warm summer.{{sfn|Bolivian montane dry forests – Myers|loc=Climate Data}} At this location the mean monthly temperatures range from {{convert|13.5|C}} in July to {{convert|18.8|C}} in November.
Yearly total precipitation is about {{convert|580|mm}}. Average monthly precipitation is below {{convert|10|mm}} in May–August, and rises to {{convert|137.4|mm}} in January.{{sfn|Bolivian montane dry forests – Myers|loc=Climate Data}}

==Ecology==

The ecoregion is in the [[Neotropical realm|neotropical]] realm, in the [[tropical and subtropical dry broadleaf forests]] biome.{{sfn|Bolivian montane dry forests – Myers|loc=WWF Abstract}}

===Flora===
[[File:Acaciacaven29b.jpg|thumb|''[[Vachellia caven]]'']]
The dry forest ecoregion is a transitional habitat between the puna grasslands higher up to the west and the Chaco scrub to the east. It contains dry slopes with scattered shrubs and columnar cacti, seasonal dry forest and wetland forest along river courses.{{sfn|Bolivian montane dry forests – Myers|loc=WWF Abstract}} Where the spiny forest has been unaltered it holds species such as ''[[Vachellia caven]]'', ''[[Prosopis alpataco]]'', ''[[Dodonaea viscosa]]'', ''[[Schinopsis marginata]]'' and [[Aspidosperma quebracho-blanco]].{{sfn|Brooks}}

===Fauna===

Several mammal species more common in the tropics are at the southern limit of their territory in the ecoregion. There appear to be a variety of feline species including [[cougar]] (''Puma concolor''), [[ocelot]] (''Leopardus pardalis''), [[Pampas cat]] (''Leopardus pajeros''), [[Geoffroy's cat]] (''Leopardus geoffroyi'') and [[jaguarundi]] (''Puma yagouaroundi'').{{sfn|Brooks}} Endangered mammals include the [[Bolivian chinchilla rat]] (''Abrocoma boliviensis'') and [[short-tailed chinchilla]] (''Chinchilla chinchilla'').{{sfn|Bolivian montane dry forests – Myers|loc=All Endangered}}

Endemic birds include the [[Bolivian recurvebill]] (''Syndactyla striatus''), [[Bolivian blackbird]] (''Oreopsar bolivianus''), [[citron-headed yellow finch]] (''Sicalis luteocephala''), [[Cochabamba mountain finch]] (''Compsospiza garleppi''), [[Bolivian warbling finch]] (''Poospiza boliviana''), [[torrent duck]] (''Merganetta armata''), [[wedge-tailed hillstar]] (''Oreotrochilus adela''), [[black-hooded sunbeam]] (''Aglaeactis pamela'') and [[grey-bellied flowerpiercer]] (''Diglossa carbonaria'').{{sfn|Brooks}} Endangered birds include the [[red-fronted macaw]] (''Ara rubrogenys'') and [[Bolivian spinetail]] (''Cranioleuca henricae'').{{sfn|Bolivian montane dry forests – Myers|loc=All Endangered}}

Endangered amphibians include the frog ''[[Telmatobius sibiricus]]''.{{sfn|Bolivian montane dry forests – Myers|loc=All Endangered}}

==Status==

The subtropical lower montane dry and moist life zones in the deep valleys between the mountains of the eastern ''Cordillera'' include the towns of [[Comarapa]], Independencia, [[Totora, Cochabamba|Totora]], [[Tapacarí]] and [[Arque]]. These are the most favorable areas for human settlement, and have long been farmed, leaving little of the original vegetation.{{sfn|Hartshorn|1979|p=13:3}}

The [[World Wildlife Fund]] gives the Bolivian montane dry forests ecoregion the status of "Critical/Endangered". The growing human population is creating urban sprawl and over-hunting, collecting wood for fuel and converting land for agriculture, causing [[habitat fragmentation]].{{sfn|Brooks}}

Protected areas include the [[Madidi National Park]] and the [[Cordillera de Sama Biological Reserve]].{{sfn|Bolivian montane dry forests – Myers|loc=WWF Abstract}}
Others are the [[Tariquía Flora and Fauna National Reserve]] and [[Torotoro National Park]].

